He was all about preserving and promoting the best of the best when it came to careers, which influenced his arguments on just about everything.

Taylor thought the US had a shot at creating the perfect system because they didn't have any pre-existing traditions to mess things up - it was a blank slate, basically. He was all about natural rights and how they're all connected - if one gets taken away, they all suffer, and the ones that are left are basically worthless. He believed these rights should be off-limits to the government. He thought the so-called "state of nature" was all about people with power and bad intentions getting ahead, but that shouldn't be the case in a civilized society.

To make this ideal society a reality, Taylor believed a government had to be designed with both good and evil in mind. He was pretty rigid in his views on dualistic morality - he thought government is basically just a reflection of human nature. He said that governments have good and bad principles, and good principles are all about protecting private property, improving agriculture, and discouraging capitalism. He thought a government with good principles would be fair no matter who was in charge, but the reality is that governments are usually run by greedy people. He believed self-interest was the driving force behind everything humans do, but it's only bad when it leads to a society that exploits others. A good government is necessary to keep humans' natural badness in check, but it needs to be watched closely to avoid adding any bad principles.

Taylor, like a lot of other super-hardcore Republicans back then, was all about interpreting the Constitution super strictly. He wanted a super limited Federal government that only had the powers explicitly stated in the Constitution. He knew a big Federal government would be expensive and likely to become a dictatorship, but he also thought that just following the literal words of the Constitution without considering the writers' intentions could be super corrupt. And, to him, the Declaration of Independence was basically the US's true charter because it clearly states that we're a bunch of separate states rather than one country.

Looking at Figure 17, it's clear that there was a huge drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. This was pretty discouraging, and it's hard to say exactly why it happened. One thing that might have contributed to it is that winter set in at our New England campus, which probably led to fewer people biking or walking to school. It's also possible that the end of the fall semester and the holiday season just got in the way – everyone was too busy finishing schoolwork and grades to bother filling out the log. Plus, the month-long break at the end of the semester probably meant a lot of people didn't need to come to campus at all. When classes resumed in January, we saw another low number of submissions, but that still doesn't explain the dip in February. It could be that people just got bored with the project after the initial excitement wore off. To counteract this, we tried something called the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which actually worked and boosted log submissions for that month. We figured out that one of our biggest challenges was getting people to stay engaged despite the natural decrease in interest, and also dealing with the holiday and semester breaks that are just part of higher education. 

Another problem we faced was that a lot of people really love driving their cars, and that's just a big part of our culture. So we had to come up with incentives to get people to try alternative modes of transportation. We gave out some pretty cool prizes, like gift cards to restaurants, coffee shops, and stores. It would have been interesting to see if bigger prizes, like a new bike or a hybrid car, would have made a difference – but unfortunately, we didn't get to try that out. We kept the same type of prizes throughout the project, but if we had announced some bigger prizes in December or January, it might have kept people engaged instead of losing interest. I mean, who wouldn't want to win a bike or a car?

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is pretty cool because it's like a security that copies an index, a commodity, or a bunch of assets, just like an index fund, but it's way more flexible and trades like a stock on the exchange.  It gives you the benefits of an index fund, like diversification, and the perks of owning a single stock, like being able to sell short, buy on margin, and even purchase just one share at a time.  These benefits are super attractive, but the fees for ETFs are way lower than the average mutual fund.  However, there are some downsides, like you have to pay a commission on any trade involving ETFs, just like with a stock order.  Another awesome thing about ETFs is that there's a huge variety of funds available.  But, it's always smart to be a savvy financial investor and check if the benefits you're told about, like diversification, are actually real, and how real they are.  For now, we're going to check out the ETF IHF and compare it to its top 10 holdings to see if owning a single ETF is just as good as owning a bunch of individual stocks.  

To make things less overwhelming, we're only going to look at the top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of the ETF's total assets.  The top 10 holdings are listed below, along with their percentage of the total assets.

By looking at how well these 10 stocks represent the ETF as a whole, we can use the current percentage of assets to calculate their contributions to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio was made up entirely of these 10 stocks, in the same proportions as the ETF has them.  The calculations for Beta and Return are included in the chart below.

From the chart, it's pretty clear that a portfolio made up of just the top 10 holdings would return 6.11% more than the ETF, a 16% increase in returns.  It's also pretty evident that the Beta of the top 10 holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF as a whole.  So far, it seems like a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could give you a higher return with a lower Beta.  But, there's a chance that the means of these two portfolios might not be all that different statistically.

To figure out if these portfolios are statistically different, we calculated the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and compared it to the standard deviation of the ETF IHF.

Dream-Land is often considered one of Edgar Allan Poe's improved poems. In this poem, Poe uses the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott thinks is linked back to the writings of Virgil. However, it's also possible that Poe got it from a more recent source - he was a big fan of German authors. 

This connection is pretty significant because it shows Poe's familiarity with Goethe's work. Karl J. Arndt noticed in his book that Poe's poem Politian is similar to Goethe's Mignon, which led him to believe that Poe might have been inspired by Goethe. 

The Oxford Companion to English Literature says that Goethe was famous for writing the poetic drama Faust, which came out in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year he died. There's a short poem called "The King of Thulé" hidden inside the second part of Faust. It's about a king who loses his wife and starts drinking heavily, then decides to die after remembering his dead queen. He throws away his goblet and walks to a cliff, where he dies. The King of Thulé and the character in Dream-Land have some pretty strong similarities, maybe even a dark opposite of Poe's own struggles with loss and drinking. 

Faust was also turned into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, just a year before Poe used the term Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum". Poe mentions Thule twice in his collected works - once in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and twice in "Dream-Land" to bookend the poem. "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land", the speaker describes Thule as a dark, lonely place with dead friends and a world without color. This sounds a lot like the King of Thulé in Goethe's poem, who's just lost his wife and is feeling pretty down. It's like the speaker in "Dream-Land" stepped right into Goethe's poem. 

Goethe was a pretty big deal in the literary world, and Poe would have likely known about him, even if it was just through his respect for Tennyson. Poe said something about how he admired Tennyson, and he would have been exposed to Goethe's work through all the reproductions that were going on after the original publication.

In California, if a customer slipped and fell on an applesauce spill in a grocery store and got hurt, can they get punitive damages if the store manager knew about the spill but didn't clean it up for half an hour because he was too busy eating dinner? A judge's probably not gonna dismiss the customer's claim for punitive damages right away. To win their case, the customer needs to show that the manager acted with a super bad and on purpose disregard for how his actions would affect people, and that his actions were really, really bad. The customer can argue that the manager should've known how bad it would be not to clean up the spill because lots of other people had slipped and gotten hurt in the store before, and he still did nothing. The customer's argument that the manager's actions were super bad isn't super strong, but it's still kind of reasonable. This is because the store had six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009 and the manager didn't do anything to make the store safer.

On October 13th at 5:00 pm, an employee of D&D Markets told the manager, Paul Martin, that there was a big applesauce spill in one of the aisles. Martin was like, "I'm on dinner break, I don't have time for customer complaints." Fifteen minutes later, another employee told Martin about the spill again, and he said the same thing. At 5:30 pm, the customer, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill and hurt her back really badly. Before Palmer got hurt, there were already five other slip-and-fall incidents reported at D&D's in 2009. Palmer is suing D&D for both regular damages and punitive damages, and we're figuring out whether to ask the judge to throw out the part of the claim about the punitive damages.

In California, people can get punitive damages if someone broke a law that wasn't related to a contract and acted with a really bad attitude, like being super mean or deceitful. The law says "malice" means either doing something on purpose to hurt someone, or doing something really, really bad with a total disregard for other people's rights or safety. Courts have said that it's like when someone knows that their actions are going to hurt people, but they do it anyway because they don't care. That's basically what the teacher in the Taylor case said in 1979.

It's crazy to think it's been almost four years since I took that course on Islam at CBC.  We had this huge debate in class about whether or not Islam is a hostile religion.  I still think that question is super relevant today, especially considering how media's view on Islam has changed since 9/11.  It's wild to think that back in 2001, we wouldn't have even considered a presidential candidate with a Muslim background like Barack Obama.  

The Prophet's biography really got me thinking.  I learned in class that Muhammad was supposed to be some kind of conqueror who forced people to convert to Islam, but the biography paints a whole different picture.  It's like, Muhammad comes across as this humble guy who's been misunderstood and even humbled himself to others.  People started to see the 'truth' in his teachings and came to him on their own.  That's pretty different from what I thought I knew about him.

What's also tripping me out is how similar the ministries of Jesus and Muhammad's 'miracles' are.  Like, there's this one story where Muhammad takes some mutton and milk and it's enough for 40 people.  I think the writers wanted to make Muhammad seem like this humble prophet who didn't need to prove anything, just lived in truth and did miracles.  That's kinda problematic because it downplays Jesus' life and personhood.  It's like they're stealing from Jesus and trying to pass it off as Muhammad's story.

There are a lot of stories in the biography that are presented as 'proof' of people converting to Islam on their own, but they're all from third-party sources.  I mean, it's like the author's trying to say 'Hey, I heard from so-and-so who heard from so-and-so,' and it just doesn't feel real.  It makes me skeptical.

What really gets me is that they're trying to make Muhammad out to be this godly, humble, and wise guy.  But history doesn't back that up, and I wonder if Muslims today even know the real story behind Muhammad's rise to power.

Looking back, it seems that the teachings and ideas that Jesus lived by got lost in the shuffle when Christianity started evolving after his death.  If we look at Christian history in general, it's clear that it's strayed further and further away from its roots.  It's like the whole world is moving forward with a growing awareness and a trend towards progress, but the traditional folks are still stuck in their ways and resistant to new ideas.  They might not be influential enough to make a huge impact, though.  I think down the line, people will start to become more aware of their Christian history and wonder what the original plans were.  They'll start to figure out which parts of the religion were added over time and what the actual message of Jesus was.  It might take a while - decades or even centuries - but eventually, things will swing back around.  A big shift will happen in Christian history, and we'll move back to the way things were when Jesus first started spreading the word.  Instead of all these added layers of doctrine, we'll strip them away, one by one, until we're back to the basics of what Jesus taught us about God.  When this movement picks up speed in the US and Europe, it'll be like a big wave that sweeps through and changes things.  People will start to worship like we did back in Jesus' day, following what he said and believed.  The church as an institution will stay strong, but it'll lead people back to the basics, not the complicated ideas that have been added over time.  You'll see a big change from all the differences within Christianity to tons of similarities and a more uniform way of thinking.  It's not the first time this has happened, either - think about how the Roman Empire used to persecute Christians, but then they became the Christian empire, or how the US used to have African-American leaders at the bottom of society, but now they're leading the way.  A similar thing is going to happen in Christianity, where people will go back to the source and make things simpler and more unified.  To make all this happen, we need to start seeing Jesus' words as metaphors, not as literal statements.  So, let's go back to the beginning - what was Christianity like back in the day?  If we go way back, we find that it all started with Judaism, which was the core of the Christian faith.  By the time the Romans took over Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., Jewish people already believed in one God, had a revealed religion, and followed the Hebrew scriptures.  But they weren't all on the same page - there were Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a bunch of regular folks, all with different ideas.

I think that The Jungle really shows how humans on the inside are pretty selfish and only think about themselves. They just try to make their lives better and don't really care about anyone else. This is super clear in the book when you look at the big factory owners and managers. All they care about is making their companies huge and rich and they don't even think about the people or the planet getting hurt because of it. Upton Sinclair writes some pretty sick stuff, like, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world". He's basically painting a picture of how messed up the pollution is and how the owners don't even care about the animals or people getting hurt. They're all about making a buck, and don't care if it hurts the environment or the people working for them. Sinclair says it pretty bluntly, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar". The owners and managers are all about making money, and they'll do whatever it takes to get it. They make people work crazy hours and then just get rid of them when they're not making enough money. Back then, there weren't really any laws to protect workers, so the owners could do whatever they wanted. The people working in the factories and living in Packingtown were basically treated like slaves. There were no organizations helping them or giving them information, and the unions were actually just making money off the poor workers. The workers were basically trapped in this system and were described as slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Sometimes authors really know how to get you to feel a certain way about important stuff. They have a bunch of tricks up their sleeve to do this, and some of them work way better than others. In his book The Great Gatsby, F. Scott Fitzgerald is like a master of these tricks. One of the things he does is pair up words that don't usually go together to make you think about a subject in a certain way. Another thing he does is take a symbol and give it meaning, then use it again to make you feel something specific. Fitzgerald used this last trick with lots of colors, including gold, green, but also white/gray and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, he builds up meaning for white/gray and red/pink, then uses that meaning to make you feel a certain way about something important.

Fitzgerald makes white/gray into a symbol of something pretty specific: uniformity. White is like, higher class and nicer, while gray is more old and faded. He sets up this meaning at the very beginning of the book by using these colors all the time. Like, Daisy and Jordan are always wearing white, and not just them - everyone's always wearing white: Nick wears white flannels to Gatsby's party, Tom wears a white shirt when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is super pale and white. Actually, the only time people aren't wearing white is when Nick's describing Gatsby's party: the halls are all gaudy and bright. Fitzgerald keeps using these colors to describe regular, boring stuff too: as Nick goes to work, he goes down the white canyons of lower New York, the names of people at Gatsby's parties are just gray names on Nick's schedule, Catherine's apartment is just one part of a long row of white apartment buildings, and so on. He even describes plain people or places as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy had a white girlhood together, there are gray cars and gray land in the valley of ashes, the little Italian kid in the train is gray, and the dog-seller is a gray old man.

After Fitzgerald builds up enough meaning with white/gray, he uses them to make you feel like some subjects are unimportant or uniform. This starts with Daisy. After a while without using these colors much, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as wearing white in a little white roadster, and you start to see her as just a uniform thing, something Gatsby wants but isn't really a person. He uses this technique with Daisy a bunch of times to make you feel like she's just a uniform addition, like when there's a gray haze around her fur collar, or when she's wearing a white dress before Tom and Gatsby's big encounter.

San Diego County is super good at growing food, thanks to its awesome weather and lots of sunshine. They grow all sorts of cool stuff like tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, and even tree fruits like peaches and lemons. Berries and honey are also super popular, and people love getting peppers. There's a huge demand for organic food in the area, and lots of local groups have super long waiting lists for their community-supported agriculture programs. People in San Diego also love buying organic eggs and milk. Many organic farms in the area even let you tour their operations and explore the land for hiking, birdwatching, and other fun stuff. This kind of setup is perfect for farmers who want to get government help while keeping the land healthy and making money through tours and other programs.

The benefits of organic farming are pretty sweet, but it's not all sunshine and rainbows. For one, it takes a lot more work and management to get rid of pests and weeds without using chemicals, and you might lose more crops than with regular farming methods. Small organic farms also can't compete with big operations when it comes to efficiency. To make things better for wildlife, you've got to do things like plant cover crops, help animals move around the land, get rid of invasive species, and make sure the plants have the right conditions to thrive. That's a lot more work and costs more money, so farmers might need some help or expertise to make it all work.

I picked a specific piece of land near the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California, as my example. It's 160 acres of beautiful chaparral, grassland, and oak woodland, right next to the Cleveland National Forest. This area is part of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion, which is covered in the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan looks at over a hundred different plants and animals, some of which are super endangered, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the mountain yellow-legged frog. Others are in trouble and might be listed as endangered soon, like the burrowing owl.

This land has been home to Native Americans for who-knows-how-long and was later settled by cattle ranchers and people who sold wood in the 1800s. It was part of an original homestead patent, so it was probably used for grazing and wood production for a long time. I picked a real piece of property from a website and looked into government programs to see what a small farmer might do to make organic farming work and keep the land safe for wildlife. I used a local organic farm in the same area as my example.

Culture is a key factor in any negotiation, but it's often more about what it's not than what it actually is. It's not one-size-fits-all; instead, it's a complex and multifaceted thing that can change from situation to situation. You can't make blanket statements like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" because they're just too broad and oversimplify things. What's more helpful is understanding how a culture affects the negotiation at hand and how its attitudes might impact the talks. When you deal with a foreign culture, you're bound to compare it to your own, and that's when the real learning happens.

To get a handle on a different culture, you might need to study its history or learn about its prejudices. The goal is to accept it for what it is, not to judge or try to change it, especially when you're in a weaker bargaining position. If you're negotiating on foreign soil, showing respect for local traditions and customs can be a game-changer. It can help you get past any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

But culture isn't just about national or international differences; it's also present within companies, too. Corporate culture can vary wildly depending on the company, from super-serious work hours to a more relaxed schedule. You can see evidence of it in things like dress codes, communication styles, and who gets hired. Take American companies, for example - they're all different, even within the same country. And it's not just about big differences between companies; even within the same company, there can be regional and urban/suburban differences. So, it's not always easy to tell what's going on beneath the surface.

When it comes to values, that's where things get really important. They're what give a culture its underlying reasons for being. If saving face or community harmony is a big deal in a culture, you can bet that a negotiator won't go out of their way to shame their company or boss in public. And if a culture values getting a hard bargain, they won't be in a rush to settle just to get a deal done. Knowing these things can help you prepare for a negotiation, but it's also a good idea to get to know your opponent on a personal level to really make the negotiation work.

"The fool has said, 'There is no God.' This quote from Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible is also the starting point for St. Anselm's argument on God's existence and is found in the beginning of his reasoning. It's interesting to note that Thomas Aquinas seems to hold a similar view as well. Since we're about to discuss both of their arguments, which are basically about the same thing, we'll assume they're both right about the existence of God - the God of the Bible. If we consider a different version of God, it would be hard to compare their arguments because they're more or less just trying to prove the existence of the one in the Bible. I think what I'm getting at is that while both of them make some solid points, neither one really does a complete job of proving God's existence.

Let's take a look at St. Anselm's argument first. Anselm basically says that to find out about God, you can look inside yourself. He says that because we already know God exists in our minds, it's impossible to imagine a world without him. When you break it down, he's saying that you don't need any outside evidence to prove God's existence - it's all about what you already know inside your head. This idea is often called faith, which means accepting something without all the facts. It's a pretty different approach from what St. Thomas Aquinas is saying.

St. Thomas thinks that you can use logic and evidence to prove God's existence without relying on faith. This would be super helpful for spreading Christianity because it would make it easier to convince new people to join without them having to believe something without proof. He's got five different logical arguments to back this up: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. What he's basically saying is that you can use logic to figure out that God exists, even if you can't see him. For example, imagine if someone told you that you're missing a puzzle piece, and you put all the others together - you can still figure out what the missing piece looks like without actually seeing it.

It's a pretty weird feeling thinking that around 2,500 years ago or so, a prince would grow up to become the Buddha. I guess this guy would ditch the whole royalty thing and find enlightenment, which, in turn, led to the creation of Buddhism. The most traditional branch of Buddhism is called Theravada Buddhism. I'm pretty sure it's changed a lot since the Buddha's time, though. You can see the difference in a place like Sri Lanka, where they have this wacky water-cutting ceremony. Everyone, monks and regular people alike, participate in it, and it's got some meaning, even though the Buddha never talked about it. These differences are all over the place, from the silly traditions to the deeper stuff that makes up the core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community has had to modify its main ideas over time, both on its own and due to external influences. Sometimes these changes come from people who don't believe in Buddhism, but other times they come from within the community itself.

You might hear some new terms in this discussion, so let's define them. An internal force refers to something that comes from within the Buddhist community, while an external force is something from outside. A hostile force is anything that harms the Buddhist community, while a benign force doesn't try to hurt or help, even if it ends up doing one or the other by accident. These terms will pop up a lot in what I'm about to say.

First off, let's talk about the basics of Theravada Buddhism – the core stuff that makes it tick. Buddhists put their trust in three key things: the Buddha, the Dhamma (which is essentially all the Buddhist texts), and the Sangha (the community). The Dhamma is made up of three main parts – the Tripitaka – which includes the Sutta Pitaka (all the Suttas), the Vinaya Pitaka (the rules of conduct), and the Abhidhamma Pitaka (the metaphysical stuff). The metaphysical stuff covers ideas like there's no permanent soul, life is full of suffering, and nothing lasts forever. If you can wrap your head around these concepts, you can break free from this cycle of death and rebirth. Along with that, you'll also kick the habit of desiring stuff, hating things, and being delusional. The Vinaya Pitaka lays out the rules for life, with five precepts for regular people (don't kill, don't lie, don't steal, don't be all weird about sex, and don't get drunk) and a bunch more rules for monks. The most important idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths: first, life is suffering; second, attachments cause suffering; and third, suffering can be overcome.

The US and Mexico have a pretty wild history that dates back to 1836 and lasted 57 years, from then to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p.145).  The craziest part of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the US took down Mexico and got its hands on Texas and the American Southwest.  There were other smaller skirmishes between the two nations, but the fighting finally died down just before the First World War.  It all started because Americans and Mexicans had major disagreements about stuff like religion, culture, and stuff they thought was important, and they also had huge differences over what they wanted to gain. (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31).  

This rivalry thing isn't unique to the US and Mexico, by the way.  Lots of countries that share borders have clashes of interests that lead to them becoming rivals.  The US and Mexico aren't that different from other countries like this.  David M. Pletcher (1977) said that "Only in Mexico and Cuba can you find long-lasting American diplomatic problems" (p. 41).  Both of these countries are right next to the US and have been at odds with it, while other Latin American countries get along pretty well with the US.  

Religious differences caused a huge rift between the US and Mexico, and this is something that's happened to a lot of other countries too.  Sally Frahm (2001) said that "if Americans were opposed to fascism and communism in the 20th century, in the 18th and 19th they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p.86).  It's kinda like how the Cold War was a mix of ideological struggles and competing interests, but in this case, it was more about the US and Mexico having different ideas about what was important.  This distrust started because the US and Mexico inherited it from their former colonial rulers - the English and Spanish.  This made it tough for the two countries to have a good relationship.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) counted 17 disputes between the US and Mexico during the 57-year rivalry period.  Most of these disputes were about border stuff, like bandits and outlaws crossing the border and causing trouble.  It wasn't until both countries started using military force to control their borders that things started to calm down (Schmitt 1974, p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) said the rivalry started to fade away as "Mexico became dependent on the US in a big way" (p. 109) and eventually ended when American ambitions changed from trying to take over land to trying to influence Mexico's economy (p.110) in the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I hit rock bottom after a mysterious illness left me disabled and unable to work. At the time, I was a nurse with a dream of becoming a scientist or journalist, but life had other plans. People kept telling me, "You'll always find a job; people will always get sick," so I chose nursing as a secure career choice. Little did I know that my security would soon be turned upside down.

Fast forward to my life at 46: I'm single, broke, and living on disability checks. I've lost count of the days when I thought I had nothing left to call my own. Every day is a struggle to survive, and my self-esteem takes a hit. But one thing I know for sure is that I couldn't have made it this far without my family and a few true friends. When disaster strikes, you realize how fragile you are, and how much you need the help of others.

My point is that life is full of emergencies – big and small. No matter how prepared you are, some things are just too big to handle on your own. So, let's stop relying solely on the government to save us and start building a safety net of our own. Instead of bailing out to build our own fallout shelters, let's learn to trust each other and ask for help when we need it.

The Conservatives talk about rugged individualism, but it was actually community and compassion that kept our ancestors going in tough times. The pioneers who trekked across the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it by going it alone – they relied on each other for support.

So, be prepared, but don't forget the importance of community. I've got my disaster kit, first aid supplies, and a stash of canned goods, but I also try to know my neighbors and look out for them. It's time for us to stop relying solely on ourselves and start building a network of people who will help each other out when things get tough.

It's still a mystery why organisms evolve the way they do. There are probably some rules or boundaries that determine which way they change over time. Even back in 1917, D'Arcy Thompson pointed out that biologists are still pretty clueless about describing the simplest living things in math terms. But more recently, math has been used to figure out how certain types of animals build their shells over time, like the way they grow and develop (Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study is working on using math to understand how animals like the ones in the Prunum family grow their shells and change over time. We're combining math with experiments to see what makes some of these animals change in certain ways. We looked at X-ray pictures of different Prunum species and used the information to create math models of their shells. These models helped us see what their shells could look like if they changed in different ways. Now we're combining these models with our experiments to learn more about how these animals evolved over time.

Think of a shell like a tube that moves through space over time. It's like a big spiral that goes around in a circle, and each part of the spiral is called a whorl. The middle of the shell is like an imaginary stick that runs through the middle of the spiral. This stick is called the columella. The speed at which the spiral grows can change, and the lines that separate each whorl are called sutures. Most shells have a big spiral at the end, which is called the body whorl. The rest of the spiral is called the spire. The tip of the spire is the apex, and the other end is the base. The animal sticks out of its shell through a hole called the aperture.

You can look at a shell from different angles, like looking at the top, bottom, front, or back. Most people look at shells with the front side facing them and the top pointing up. 

There's a way to count the whorls on a shell. First, look at the shell from the top and find the first line where the whorls start to separate. Then draw a line to divide the shell in two. Count the whorls from this line, and you can even estimate a quarter of a whorl if you need to.

A shell is like a series of holes that move through time and space as the animal grows its shell. You can follow the path of the holes by looking at the center of each whorl and the size of the hole. This path can be drawn and mathematically explained. Once you have the math formula, you can change the rules and see how the animal's shell changes.

It's been a decade since Indonesia's neonatal and infant mortality rates have changed much.  Even though the country is doing pretty well in achieving some of the Millennium Development Goals, like getting clean water and sanitation, the progress in child and maternal health is nowhere near what it needs to be to reach its targets by 2015.  In the next few sections, I'll be talking about the reasons behind this lack of improvement, and you'll see why Indonesia needs to focus on strengthening its healthcare system rather than just working on individual programs.

Indonesia has made some progress in getting skilled workers at births, with 72% of births now getting this kind of care.  But this number is a bit misleading since it includes traditional workers like midwives who can't provide medical help if a pregnancy gets complicated - which is why a lot of maternal deaths are due to hemorrhage.  Additionally, there's been a drop in the percentage of kids under five who get treated by a health professional for diarrhea, and the data on post-natal care is pretty incomplete, but it's clear that it's a big problem all over the country.

C-section rates are still pretty low at 4%, and that's got some major implications.  The rate is 7% in cities, but only 2% in rural areas, which shows that healthcare services are mostly focused on city areas.  There's also a huge gap in access to healthcare between the richest and poorest families - 27% to be exact.  This means the poor are having a hard time getting the care they need, probably because they can't afford it.

So, the big question is how to make things better, starting with getting more healthcare services available.  Should Indonesia focus on developing special programs or just making the overall healthcare system stronger?  It's clear that special programs can get fast results, but they also have some big drawbacks.  One problem is that when you invest a lot in one area, other areas might get left behind.  Another issue is that all these separate programs can get really confusing and make a lot of extra paperwork.

Victorian novels are known for their intricate details and their focus on the aristocracy of the time period.  Two novels that deviate from this norm are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights.  Instead of following the typical Victorian style, these novels incorporate a sense of mystery and a touch of the bizarre, which helps to deepen our understanding of the characters' motivations and emotions. These atypical elements give us insight into their inner workings, making them feel more real and relatable.

As Fagin's character in Oliver Twist was walking between Sikes and Crackit, arguing, he couldn't shake off the feeling that he was still there; the words they were saying echoed in his mind, and when he snapped out of it, he found himself talking to them.  Suddenly, he jumped back at the sound of gunfire and was whisked away by an unseen force.  Through this disorienting experience, a nagging sense of pain lingered, wearing him down and tormenting him.

In both novels, this sense of mystery often manifests itself through dream sequences or dreamlike states.  In Oliver Twist, these bizarre events give us a glimpse into Oliver's inner world, revealing what hurts him and how he perceives the events unfolding around him.  When Oliver is shot in chapter 28, he relives the experience vividly, as if it's a dream, while struggling to find help.  The passage emphasizes Oliver's lack of control over his situation, as well as his dire circumstances, which is evident in his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit.  The shooting overwhelms him, numbing all his senses, and he feels his despair wash over him again, this time laced with fear rather than surprise.  With Oliver being overwhelmed, the question arises as to who is responsible for his misfortune, since it certainly wasn't him.  This event reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over his life, and that he's unable to even attempt to take charge of an event's outcome, even when his life is on the line.  A growing sense of defeat is also implied, as if Fagin has broken him, forcing him to accept this despair and lose his ability to react.

The day after the shooting passed quickly – it was over before it began – and night fell again, a long and dreadful silence that seemed to last forever, yet was over in what felt like an instant.

A couple years back, I worked with a pretty cool after-school program where I helped Elementary school kids with their homework and whatever they were struggling with in class. My thing was reading and English, though. One of the instructors asked me to work with a little dude named Adrian, who was having a super tough time reading. I figured something was up; it was weird because he knew some letters super well, but others were a total mystery to him. I'm pretty sure he was of Latin background, and he spoke English like a pro, but I was still confused. We struggled through that until the day I met his mom. I was hanging out with him while the rest of the group went on a field trip, and his mom showed up. She only spoke Spanish, and my Spanish skills are basically non-existent, but we managed to communicate somehow. It hit me like a ton of bricks then: Adrian could totally read, but he just didn't know the English alphabet super well. I don't know if that realization helped him much, but I hope he's doing way better now.

I'm telling this story because it highlights the problem of language barriers in schools, especially here in California. It's not always as obvious as it seems, even for kids who speak perfect English. Reading can be super tough for them too. We all agree that this is a problem, so what's the solution? For Adrian, it was pretty simple: just some extra tutoring in English reading, especially the alphabet and pronunciation. But for the kids who barely speak English, it's way more complicated. There's no one-size-fits-all answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes – none of these things alone will fix it. We need to combine them all.

The dual language system is actually a pretty great idea, not just for kids who speak Spanish at home, but for all kids. Apparently, kids in two-way bilingual education programs do way better in school. A lot of people freak out about this idea, thinking it's a waste of resources and that most kids won't benefit. But that's just not true. If we made this the norm, not the exception, all kids would benefit from it. So how do we do it? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? That's a bit unrealistic. What we could do is have special bilingual aids, tutors, or whatever you want to call them, to help out.

Most of us are told from a young age that there's something greater than us out there - something we can't fully comprehend. Some of us attend Sunday school, others go to Temple, and some search within themselves for answers. Many of us stick to the faith passed down by our parents, but some of us reject it entirely, thinking there's nothing beyond what we can see in our own little world. We might change our minds and try a different value system later on. Whatever path we choose, we're on a journey to figure out who we are based on our own unique spiritual perspectives. We seek a guiding light to lead us out of the dark and into the light.

My dad told me that cardinals are his favorite bird when I asked. We were sitting on our front porch, listening to the rain pounding on the tin roof, the sound echoing off the wet plants by the edge of the porch. He was staring out into the rain, a look that was both searching and remembering. He'd lost a lot of weight lately, and his old clothes hung loosely on his frame. His hair was thinner, too. I felt scared and alone, and I didn't know how to talk to him about how much I'd miss him without making it too real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, and joined him in staring out into the rain.

That was the last time I saw my dad. He passed away in December, just five days before my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation hadn't made him feel better, but had kept him alive for a few more months longer than the doctors said he'd make it. I wondered what the point was in suffering so long if it didn't get any easier. If God existed, I thought, he'd stopped listening to me a long time ago. I didn't say any prayers that night because I didn't want to ask for anything. I just wanted to remember my dad the way he was, not the way he left.

I didn't watch him die because I couldn't bear to see the person who made me leave this life behind. I wanted to remember him for who he was, not how he went. I knew my dad better than anyone, and I knew he wouldn't have wanted me to witness his final moments. I curled up in a ball in bed for three days, waiting for the news. No one even called me.

The term "Gothic Novel" is a bit of an irony, an oxymoron combining "old" and "new," as Ian Watt so cleverly points out in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. Throughout history, the Gothic mode has been praised and bashed, with some people thinking it's all superficial and others finding depth in its "terrible sublime" qualities (Burke). When Horace Walpole created the original "Gothic Novel," The Castle of Otranto, he mixed elements from ancient romances and modern novels to invent a fresh way of writing. He called it "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre drew inspiration from medieval theatre, architecture, and traditions, even though it was initially seen as old-fashioned or unsophisticated compared to the modern world. The blend of the theatrical and the new format of the novel, which lets readers see the characters' inner thoughts, is what made Gothic novels last and stay relevant, becoming both outdated and new to readers from different time periods.

One of the key Gothic ideas is the concept of Chivalry. In The Castle of Otranto, the medieval idea of chivalry, which was meant to create a proper knight, was taken and transformed. Chivalry was important to Gothic writers because it represented the ideal knight – brave, honorable, and competent – and they saw a lack of those qualities in their own time. By using chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" was idealized and romanticized (foreshadowing the future of Gothic to Romantic) and used to try to improve the present. When Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto, he was living through a tumultuous time and was worried about the future. Feeling let down by politics and unfairly accused, he might have thought that the supposed good nature of people in the gothic era was lost in modern society. This idea is clear in characters like Frederic, who's described as:

The description of Frederic includes many chivalric images; he's a prince who's suffered, been affected by tragedy, and supposedly killed by infidels. This exaggerated portrayal of the "gallant and courteous Knight" introduces the Gothic trope of excess, which will become a recurring theme (66).

So, you want to know about supply chain management? It's basically the whole process of getting stuff from the person who wants it (the customer) all the way back to the raw materials that make it. It's like a big chain of events that happens really fast. The term supply chain management was invented by Keith Oliver back in 1982. He said it's all about planning, implementing, and controlling the whole process so you can satisfy customers quickly and efficiently. There are six main parts to a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these parts to give the best customer service ever.

Production is the very first step in the process. It's like the foundation of the whole thing. You need to figure out when, why, where, and how you're going to make the stuff. To do that, you have to know what the customer wants, so you look at the market. The market is like a big indicator of what people are into. Once you know what they want, you can decide what to make and how much of it. After that, you figure out where to make it and which factory is best for quality and quantity. You also have to make sure the customer is happy, or else it's all pointless.

The next step is scheduling work and taking care of the equipment. This is super important because if you don't plan everything out, it can cost you a lot of time and money in the long run. I know this from my old job at Wal-Mart and Target. We had a super specific plan for everything, from how the uniforms looked to when the shipments came in. It made everything run smoothly and nobody got confused.

The second key element is supply. This is all about deciding what you're good at and who you should partner with. Let's say you make a bunch of different products and each one needs a different setup. You have to decide which one is best for each part of the process. You might even outsource some of the work to other companies to save time and money. The goal is to be fast and flexible while keeping costs low.

I was walking down the street the other day and saw this crazy sign being held by Ellen Page, star of Juno. It read, "Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign says." I thought it was pretty wild. Burma, or Myanmar, is a country in Southeast Asia where the government is super strict. They took over in 1962 after a big power struggle. Last year, the people there started protesting, led by monks who wore these orange robes. The protests were called the Saffron Revolution, and at first, the government was kinda cool with it, but things quickly escalated into a full-blown conflict. The military started attacking the monks and their monasteries, and anyone who was seen as a threat was arrested or worse. Foreign journalists were even killed, like this Japanese dude named Kenji Nagai. We're not even sure how many people died, but some reports say thousands.

This isn't new, though. Governments have been trying to shut down dissent for ages. The ancient Romans thought their emperors were gods, and the Japanese still think their emperors are, like, actual gods. Our current president talks to some crazy dude named Ted Haggard, who's like, the leader of some super right-wing group. It's like, what's the difference between them and the Chinese government, which killed all these people in Tiananmen Square in '89? The official story says a few hundred died, but other reports say it was way more, like 2,000-3,000. And then there was the Rwandan genocide, where Hutu militia groups killed all these Tutsis and moderates. Hitler's whole "Third Reich" thing was pretty much the same deal.

Duke Ellington’s impact on jazz is super big because he was around for so long and was so creative with his orchestra. Some of his songs, like the ones for this project, don't even have him on the piano, but as a composer, Ellington was a master at writing music that made each band member shine. He created this framework where soloists could just go wild and improvise, and at the same time, he'd write pieces that highlighted each band member's style. This way, he made the whole orchestra sound super cool and original. Ellington was also really good at understanding how each player sounded alone, and how they fit together in the group, which allowed him to write some of the most genius and amazing jazz pieces ever.

The Grove Music dictionary talks about how Ellington used voice as a "jazz instrument" in his whole career, and it's a good example of this in his song Creole Love Call. It's a slow, bluesy piece where he used voice to add some extra texture and color, without even needing lyrics. This song also shows how Ellington was great at making his soloists sound awesome, which he did in a lot of his music. The song has six different parts, and each one is like a mini-story. 

Chorus 1: It starts with the voice and the reeds talking to each other, with the voice being super smooth and melodic at first, but then getting a bit rougher at the end.
Chorus 2: Then there's a muted trumpet solo that takes the basic melody and makes it sound even better, with some extra notes that make it sound really cool.
Chorus 3: After that, there's a clarinet solo that's super fast and high-pitched, with a piano phrase that's really funky.
Chorus 4: The next part is like a big echo of the first chorus, but with the brass and reed sections talking to each other.
Chorus 5: The final part is the most intense, with the reeds starting to talk back, and the brass section making some really cool rhythms.
Chorus 6: The last part goes back to the first chorus, but this time the voice is using a special technique called the "growl" to sound like it's playing an instrument.
The last part is just a quick tag with a vocal run and some weird, dissonant sounds from a trombone.

This is just one example of how Ellington used voice to add some extra flavor to his music. In his song Hot and Bothered, he combines his skill at making the orchestra sound tight with his ear for making sounds that sound really cool. In that song, he has a call and response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing, where they use both vocal and instrumental parts to make something really rich and cool. It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing) takes this idea even further, as Ellington uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton to introduce the melody on muted trombone, and it sounds amazing.

I've had this thing inside me for a while now - this feeling that something's missing. It started when I was 14, right when I was getting into the whole teenage scene. Now I'm 17, and it's still there. I've come to realize I'm looking for someone, not just something, but I just can't seem to find anyone I'm into. Some guys have tried to get my attention, and they've all gone through the usual awkward stages, but none of them have been able to hold my interest. I've spent years trying to figure out what's going on with this, and I've come up with a bunch of ideas, but nothing that really makes sense. So I just keep living life, still trying to figure it out.

At home, things are pretty chill. My parents are super laid-back and rarely argue about anything. The only times they do get into a fight are when they disagree with my independent streak. I'm the calm and collected daughter of two super mellow parents, but I'm like the complete opposite - I'm all about living life to the fullest and being true to myself. But today was different. I was walking around the house trying to find some new ideas, when I heard my mom let out a blood-curdling scream from the kitchen. I ran in there, freaking out, and saw my mom on the ground, clearly in agony. She was saying "Ow" over and over, and I knew I had to act fast. I rushed to her side and helped her up. She told me to take her to the hospital - I could tell she was in a lot of pain. I got her to the car and drove her there myself.

When we got to the hospital, the smell of disinfectant and sickness hit me, but I was too worried about my mom to feel scared. I helped her onto a rolling bed and called for the doctors. They took her in right away, and I was left sitting there, worried sick.

Apparently, my mom had slipped off a stool while trying to grab a vase from the top shelf. I was relieved when the doctors took her in and started checking her out. Now I'm just waiting and hoping everything turns out okay.

This research aimed to demonstrate that sticking to the "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high score on the "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet" scale, is linked to a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet that consists of higher consumption of plant-based foods, including fruits, nuts, whole grains, legumes, and monounsaturated fats, and lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate amounts of alcohol are allowed.

Past studies showed that following the Med diet was associated with a lower risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, and an intervention study found that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the total-to-high-density lipoprotein cholesterol ratio in obese individuals. However, these previous studies didn't focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This study involved 74,886 women aged 38 to 63 years old, who were part of the Nurses' Health Study, a research project following 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. The authors calculated the aMed diet score six times from 1984 to 2004 using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" that assessed participants' nutrient intake during the previous year. More than 95% of the nurses continued participating throughout the 20-year study period. These questionnaires were validated through other studies. The researchers verified reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke by reviewing medical records, hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. If records weren't available, cases were classified as "probable" and included in the study, with around 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts falling into this category. Age, smoking status, body mass index, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were calculated for each questionnaire, and starting in 1986, the participants' leisure-time physical activity was also evaluated.

To reduce random variation and better represent long-term dietary intake, the researchers averaged together the aMed scores from repeated questionnaires over time (averaging scores from two prior years). The study adjusted for potential "confounders" (factors that could affect the results) by accounting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Using a statistical method called Cox proportional-hazard modeling, the study found that a higher aMed diet score was associated with a lower risk of CHD and stroke in the women. Over the course of 20 years, the researchers identified 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined). Women who scored highest on the aMed diet were less likely to experience both CHD and stroke compared to those who scored lowest (with a relative risk of 0.71).

So, let's talk about this super crazy financial crisis that hit the United States back in 2007. It was like, a total nightmare – unemployment went up, the housing market went down, and all these huge corporations were left in shambles. We're still dealing with the aftermath, so it's time to figure out what happened and how to stop it from happening again. In a nutshell, the financial crisis was caused by some pretty selfish and clueless politicians who pushed banks and companies to give out these sketchy sub-prime loans to people who couldn't really afford them. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were forced to buy up and package these bad loans into these super complex financial things called CDOs and CDSs. When people started defaulting on their loans, the banks were like, "uh-oh, we don't have enough money!" and they tried to pawn off the problem onto these repackaged mortgages they'd already sold, and then onto the rest of the economy.

It all started back in 1999 when Clinton was trying to get re-elected. He wanted to be popular, so he relaxed some lending rules, which set the stage for this whole sub-prime mess that happened seven years later. Steven Holmes from the New York Times was like a total genius and predicted this whole thing would go down. He said, "Hey, Fannie Mae is under pressure from the government to give out more loans to low-income people, and also from its stockholders who just want more profits." And then he nailed it: "But if there's an economic downturn, Fannie Mae will be in big trouble and the government will have to bail it out, just like they did with the savings and loan industry in the 80s." Yeah, that's exactly what happened.

A bunch of other factors contributed to the economy going haywire. There were all these new, super complicated mortgage things like adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and CDOs that tied up the whole economy with the housing market. This made households and financial markets super vulnerable to even small changes in housing prices. And, well, the housing bubble burst, and all these financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were like, "Oh no, what do we do?" The top five investment banks were stuck with $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt, which is like, a huge chunk of the USA's GDP. In the end, some of these banks got sold for a steal, while others got dismantled or forced to become "normal" banks with lots of rules to follow. Fannie and Freddie were in huge trouble too, with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and the government had to step in and take control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition - the villain of the writer's world.  It's that part in your story where you try to take off like a superhero, but end up face-planting into a pool of boring text that puts your readers to sleep or makes them vow to never come back to your site.  I know Dr. Merlin has been known to scream at her computer when she gets stuck in Exposition Limbo, and not in the cool, edgy way.

Exposition is the nemesis that every writer needs to conquer.  Even if you know the "Show, don't tell" rule, you're still likely to find yourself stuck in a sea of unnecessary details that don't move the plot forward.

Exposition is when you dump a ton of backstory, history, or info onto your readers without giving them a chance to breathe.  It's like the character in your story telling another character their entire life story in one breath - as seen in those epic tales like "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, it's you, the author, doing the telling instead.

To illustrate this, imagine reading a story where the heroine meets her beloved at a certain time and place, gets married in style, and then has her husband brutally murdered in front of her.  You wouldn't expect this whole sequence to take two whole pages, right?  And you certainly wouldn't expect the husband and wife to only get two lines of dialogue each.  You'd want the author to spend some quality time developing the husband's character, showing how much he loves his wife through his words and actions, and revealing how she's changed and grown because of him.  This would make his death even more impactful and your connection to the heroine deeper.

In short, you'd want to add some meat to the bare bones of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."  As a writer, it's your job to provide that meat.  Sometimes it's tempting to rush through certain parts, but don't be tempted - give your readers what they want and need to care about your story.

I just watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one I saw was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The top story was about some serious stuff in Ashley, Ohio - a dude named Shad Hostettler had stabbed his wife. They only showed a quick bit on this, like two minutes, 'cause it was still developing. All they said was that he had stabbed her multiple times and got arrested. I think they handled it pretty fairly. 
	Next up was a story about a shooting in Sharon Woods. Some 18-year-old named Travis Buyers got shot, but they didn't have any suspects or arrests. The SWAT team was investigating. This story felt kinda short, and I think it might've been because the victim was a black kid from a black neighborhood. I've noticed this pattern before - when a minority gets hurt, the media usually doesn't give it much airtime. But if a white person gets hurt, it's huge news. 
	The next story was about a Med-Flight helicopter getting a .22 caliber bullet hole in it. They said they think it happened somewhere specific, and Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-grand reward for any tips that help catch the shooter. 
	Then there was a story about some rain and thunderstorms coming on Saturday. They said the weekend was gonna be in the mid-to-low eighties, but it was a pretty short clip - I think they just wanted to keep us watching. 
	They also did a piece on a robbery at a UDF on Clime Road in Columbus. They said the perp was a dark-skinned black guy wearing a hoodie, and they spent a weird amount of time emphasizing how dark he was. 
	Lastly, they had a story about Rene Rodriguez, a Texas dude who was convicted of running a big marijuana operation from Texas to Ohio. He got sentenced to 300 months in prison, which I thought was a weird way to say 25 years. They also mentioned he's Hispanic, but I'm not sure why that was relevant.

There's a bond between brothers that's like a fortress, unbreakable and unshakable. It's a bond that holds a bunch of complicated emotions like love, pride, jealousy, and even cruelty. When you have a brother, you kinda get them, you know? They're like a mirror image of yourself, and they can only see themselves when they look at you. But it's when things get really tough that you find out what's really going on in that bond. It's then that you see the good and the bad, and it's not always easy to deal with. When you can look a brother in the eye and see your own reflection staring back at you, you're forced to confront who you really are and what you're really made of. It's in their actions and the consequences of those actions that you see what someone's really like. This theme is explored in "The Scarlet Ibis", where two brothers are on a wild adventure that goes totally wrong. Their journey is like a rollercoaster of emotions, with bitter disappointment and intense pride clashing in the end. Only one of them gets out alive, but the other brother's spirit lives on.

The story is all about how one brother feels, especially about pride. He's got this huge ego and he wants his little brother, Doodle, to be someone he can teach all the cool stuff to, like how to hold his breath and run fast. But Doodle's got a weak heart, and it's like his whole dream is crushed. The big brother's got a mix of emotions, from anger to love, and it's hard to say which one's stronger. He even thinks about doing something crazy, but when Doodle smiles, he starts to feel all warm and fuzzy inside. It shows that deep down, he really loves his little bro. The story's all about how this complicated bond between brothers works, and how it can drive you crazy, but also how it can be super strong.

So, the brain is basically a super cool, super advanced machine that can do all sorts of crazy stuff. As technology has gotten better and better, people have come up with new ways to describe how the brain works. At first, it was like a piece of wax, then a scroll, then a book, and now it's like a super powerful computer. However, these comparisons aren't perfect and can sometimes lead to wrong conclusions.

So, let's start with the basics. The brain takes in information from our senses, which turn things like touch, sound, and light into electrical signals. It then processes this info in two different ways: bottom-up and top-down. Think of bottom-up like putting together a puzzle – it starts with simple pieces of info like color, shape, and edges, and then puts them together to figure out what you're seeing. Top-down is like using what you already know to help you make sense of things faster. For example, if you see a picture of a black box on a white background, top-down processing can help you figure out it's a box, not a hole in the background.

Once the brain has processed some info, it decides which signals are important and sends them to the right places. It's like having a filter that says, "Hey, don't worry about those individual blades of grass, but let's pay attention to your name when someone says it really loudly." There are lots of steps to processing, and attention plays a big role in deciding what's important and what's not.

But before the brain can process info, it has to store it somehow. There are different kinds of memory, like short-term and long-term, and they work in different ways. When we first get info, it gets encoded, or put into the brain in a way that makes sense. This encoding depends on what kind of info it is – like how words look, sound, or mean. Once it's stored, the brain has to keep it around. Scientists think that short-term memory might be like a temporary electrical signal, while long-term memory is stored in special proteins.

There are all sorts of theories about how the brain organizes information. Some are based on how people remember things, some on computer science, and some on brain science. One cool theory is the semantic network, where ideas are connected to each other like a web. For example, the idea of a "chair" is linked to a "table," which is linked to "wood," and so on.

Aldous Huxley warns us about the dangers of both technology and the capitalistic system that supports it in his dystopian novel, Brave New World. In this world, people are conditioned to prioritize community and instant happiness above all else. The citizens are basically pawns in a larger game, forced to conform to the World Controller's ideology. By looking at the book through a Marxist lens, you can see that Huxley is basically saying that this is a bad idea. He uses words and ideas from Marxism, like homogeny and reification, to show that he thinks this system is messed up.

The way Huxley uses satire to criticize capitalism is pretty cool. He's talking about something called false consciousness, which is like when people don't know how they're really connected to the people around them, especially in terms of money. In Brave New World, people are so focused on their own stuff that they can't see the bigger picture. The World Controller is basically controlling everyone, making them think that all they need to do is consume and indulge in stuff. This is super obvious in how the lower classes, like the Deltas and Gammas, are controlled through hypnopædia. They don't really have any control over their own lives. They're just following what they're told. This is basically an example of hegemony, which is when a group of people is controlled by a smaller group of people. The people in control are the ones who get to decide what's best for everyone else, and the lower classes just go along with it. They're basically buying into this system that's set up to keep them down.

In Brave New World, relationships between people are really superficial. People don't really care about each other, they just care about how they look and what they can get out of each other. It's like Huxley is saying that technology and capitalism are taking away people's free will and their ability to be themselves. Love and strong emotions don't exist in this world, and people are just going through the motions. The way the characters interact with each other is really shallow, like when the guys talk about the women just because of how they look, or when the women talk about their shallow relationships. This is all a commentary on how people are just following the rules and not really thinking for themselves. They're all just going along with what the system tells them to do, which is basically a Marxist idea about how the working class is brainwashed into thinking they're better than everyone else as long as they keep consuming and following the rules.

I've been attending University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters, and navigating the campus can be a real pain. Like many others, I've had my share of struggles getting around. During my freshman year, I lived in an East Halls dorm room, basically as far east as you can get on campus, except for the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. It would take me up to 25 minutes to get to places like Willard building near the center of campus on foot, especially when the weather was bad, which it often is in State College. I talked to an alum who's only a bit older than me, and they told me that not long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the school by huge empty spaces. Now those areas are filled with sports fields, new buildings like the Creamery and health services building, and apartments. As the campus keeps growing, getting from one place to another is becoming more and more of a challenge. On a college campus, the best solution to this problem is the humble bicycle. But just having a bike isn't enough; students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be designed with bicyclists in mind.

I recently talked to a friend who got back into biking after a few years off, and he said it's crazy he ever stopped. "Bikes are awesome," he said, "for a few years it wasn't cool to ride a bike, but it's the only way to get around." Not only is biking good for you, it's also super efficient. A bowl of oatmeal and some physical activity can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergrads, I now live off campus, just as far from the center as some dorms. The smartest move I made this year was buying a bike. Every day I have class in Thomas building, which is a 25-minute walk from my place. But with my bike, I can cut that time down to just 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only catch is that Pollock Road is the most direct route to Thomas building from my house, but it's not always the easiest road to navigate, bike or not. There are some good things about walking too, but personally, I don't have time for it. If I didn't have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option, and it would take me an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That's over two and a half hours every week, which is just too much time to waste.
