They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.

As I pursue my education in social work, I'm set on a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to make a difference in the lives of abused or neglected kids, and to lend a helping hand to struggling families. Some key values that I'll bring to the social work field are service, respect, ethics, and a commitment to improving relationships and my own professional skills – staying on top of my game, so to speak. These aren't just important for social workers; they're personal values for me too.

Growing up, I always wanted to help others, but I wasn't sure which career path to take. During high school and college, I saw people dodging their problems and some dealing with issues in not-so-great ways. After witnessing some pretty tough stuff, I decided to go for a degree in Psychology. Still unsure about my next step, I took a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. That summer, a friend introduced me to a 16-year-old kid who was really struggling – he'd run away from his abusive parents. The next day, he called the cops on them. I went to their house, where I told the police about my concerns and shared that I had a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. They asked me to speak with the parents since there wasn't much they could do. When I talked to the parents, they seemed really nervous and made excuses for their kid's actions. After that, I seriously considered a career in social work to help kids deal with family drama.

Social justice is another value that's super important in the social work field. We say that individuals matter, but in reality, we're often more about conforming to old traditions than being unique. If we're all about mourning lost individuals, then why do we try to be like everyone else? I'm an individual and I don't want to put limits on myself to fit in with the crowd. In high school and college, I spoke out against social injustice whenever I could – I colored my hair weird colors, wore clothes that fit my personality, got my ears pierced in a more alternative way, joined GSBA, and stood up against racism and discrimination whenever I saw it. I believe in social justice, and I'll keep fighting against it.

The following study delves into the biological and sociocultural models associated with insomnia. The biological model zeroes in on the genetic factors that are passed down through generations as well as the medical aspects of overall health. On the other hand, the sociocultural model looks at how environmental factors, such as ethnicity, demographics, socioeconomic status, and more, contribute to the disorder. This paper will explore and examine the various pieces of research related to these models in order to better grasp their intricacies. An analysis of the research findings and their strengths and weaknesses will be presented in this review.

Insomnia can be categorized into three distinct groups: primary sleep disorders, sleep disorders connected to other mental health issues, and sleep disorders linked to medical complications or substance use. The primary sleep disorders encompass Dyssonmias and Parasomnias, while sleep disorders related to other mental health issues are connected to Axis I or Axis II disorders. Dyssonmias include Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified. Primary Insomnia involves difficulty in achieving or maintaining a restful sleep, whereas Primary Hypersomnia is characterized by an excessive desire to stay awake, both lasting for at least a month. Narcolepsy is marked by cataplexy and/or automatic REM. 

The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genetic factors, heritable traits, and the physiological aspects of sleep. Research has shown that neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin play a crucial role in regulating sleep and wakefulness. A study on mice found that phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons are specifically responsible for sleep/wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor promotes sleep, while its inhibition can lead to reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time, as discovered by Matsuki et al. (2009). This study implies that findings from animal models can be applied to human studies, indicating a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. This has significant sociocultural implications, as the phenotype could be inherited, regulating sleep, and any alterations in the receptor could naturally disrupt sleep patterns for an individual. This, in turn, could impact daily life, including academic and professional responsibilities, and mundane tasks that require focus.

This paper explores Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), a condition that affects the way the brain handles what we hear. Put simply, people with CAPD can hear just fine, but their brain can't properly sort out what's going on. I mean, imagine trying to have a conversation at a loud party - it's hard to focus on what one person is saying when there's a lot of background noise, right? That's kinda what's happening with CAPD. It's not that they can't hear, it's just that their brain can't separate the good stuff from the noise. 

CAPD has been around since the 1950s, when researchers first started studying kids with communication problems. They called it "auditory imperception" back then, but now we know it as CAPD. A team of Italian researchers, Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari, actually started developing tests for CAPD back in 1954. Later, in 1961, Kimura came up with a model that explained how the brain handles different sounds, and it's been a topic of study ever since.

So, what does CAPD look like? Well, it can manifest in all sorts of ways. Some people might have trouble telling where sounds are coming from, or they might get confused by different sounds happening at the same time. They might struggle to recognize patterns or changes in speech, like when someone says something sarcastically. It's like their brain gets all mixed up and can't untangle what's going on. And if you're trying to listen to two people talking at the same time, it can be super hard for them to block out one sound and focus on the other.

To figure out if someone has CAPD, doctors and other specialists use a bunch of different tests. They might ask questions and observe how people respond to different sounds, like a bunch of words or numbers all at once. It's not like there's one magic test that can diagnose it, but it's all about getting a sense of how the brain handles sound. Some tests even use fancy equipment to record sounds and see how the brain responds. And, at the end of the day, there's no known cause for CAPD, so it's all about figuring out the best way to help people deal with it.

Teachers in mainstream classrooms can help out by being aware of these common "red flags" - you know, the signs that might indicate someone has CAPD. They can use special techniques to make it easier for students with CAPD to focus and understand what's going on. By being understanding and accommodating, teachers can make a big difference in the lives of students with CAPD.

It seems like Twelfth Night is saying that disguises can be pretty useful for getting away with huge deceptions for a long time, but in the end, you gotta ditch that new disguise or risk losing yourself in the process forever. The thing is, getting rid of that deception can also make you pretty alienated from others, since some people might not take it well. You're basically stuck between saving yourself or keeping your relationships with the people around you. While some will be all chill about it, others will freak out and be totally turned off by the whole thing. 

The part about disguising yourself as the opposite gender gets really tricky because it brings up a bunch of other issues. Like, why do people do it in the first place? In Viola's case, she pretends to be a dude so she can protect herself from people trying to hurt her. She's a bit like, "Hey, I'll just go to this captain and he'll help me hide out near Count Orsino so I can serve him." (She's talking about her plan at the beginning of Act 5, Scene 1.)

So, Viola dresses up as a guy and it works, but it also makes her lose touch with the women around her and makes her miss out on a support system. And to make matters worse, she's so good at pretending to be a dude that Olivia gets all confused and starts thinking she's a guy named Sebastian and falls for her. Then there's the whole thing with Viola and Orsino, who's all like, "You've told me a million times you wouldn't love a woman like me." (Act 5, Scene 1, again.)

But, looking at it from today's perspective, Twelfth Night can be seen as a way to show how deception can help people figure out things they've been hiding, especially for Olivia and Orsino. There are some parts that seem to hint that Olivia might be secretly into women, but I guess that's not really what it's about. Olivia's more likely just making fun of people who judge others based on looks. It's pretty clear when she starts to really like Sebastian and forgets all about Cesario/Viola. It's like she says, "You're like a sister to me." (Act 5, Scene 1.) It sounds like Olivia is just messing with people who judge based on appearance.

You can't even begin to understand the real deal about German colonial rule. I mean, yeah, it was super brutal, especially when it came to the Ovaherero and Nama genocide in South West Africa. But you can't just lump the whole empire into one neat little package. It was all over the place with different policies and styles in every colony, just like how it varied in geography. Education was no exception - some colonies were actually doing pretty well, like German East Africa (now Tanganyika) where the Brits found a bunch of super smart and literate Africans in 1919. They were even giving German colonial efforts in Kamerun and other places a thumbs up from authors back in the day.

But then there's South West Africa (now Namibia), where things were super different. Unlike East Africa where the government was all about setting up schools and educating the locals, in South West Africa they basically left it all to the missionaries who were getting pretty minimal support from the government. Yet, they still managed to throw a ton of resources at educating Europeans in the colony, setting up state schools and regulating the missionaries. This all had some major long-term effects on South West Africa, even after the Germans were gone. While other German colonies were rocking with educated and literate Africans, in South West Africa "most people were basically clueless, uneducated, and illiterate." There were a bunch of reasons for this, and I want to dive deeper into them in this paper, especially the attitudes of settlers and colonial officials towards the locals.

There's a bunch of research out there on education in the German colonies, but most of it is in German and from the early 20th century. These early works were all about describing the educational systems in these colonies. Later stuff in English expanded on it by comparing education in different colonies and getting into the nitty-gritty of specific aspects. It turns out that every colony was doing its own thing with education, and the most famous work on this topic is probably Cohen's study of South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the two and talks about the factors that made them so different. Apparently, the big settler population in South West Africa is a major reason for the difference.

South West Africa was pretty chill for Europeans, with a relatively nice climate, but most of the land was basically a desert. This made it super appealing to Europeans, and by 1913 there were almost 15,000 of them living there, which was way more than in any other colony except East Africa.

Heavy metal music has undergone a huge transformation over the past 100 years, expanding into so many different genres that it's a real challenge to make a list of them all. To make matters even more complicated, most of these genres, like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, have spawned numerous sub-genres within their own domains. I'm gonna argue that the sub-genre of heavy metal rock has become one of the most expressive and diverse genres of popular music in the last 40 years. It's expressive because it showcases a wide range of emotions, mostly on the darker side of the spectrum, but also because it's incredibly flexible, allowing people to take it in their own unique direction. 

You could say we've reached a point in the heavy metal movement where it's hard to pinpoint what exactly heavy metal is, given how many niches and sub-niches it's branched out into by incorporating elements from other genres. But to truly understand the metal music that's everywhere today, you gotta understand the metal movement itself and where it all started. It's actually defined by darkness, heavy metal being the "music of more" - more bass, more volume, more intensity, and more theatrics. It's about musicians who really know their craft, and that skill shines through in the music. Some say metal is also a movement heavily influenced by psychedelics, which were all the rage in the 70s, and were used as a creative outlet for musicians to tap into their wilder side. This music often deals with the darker aspects of life, which was a new and exciting thing back in the day when most popular music was pretty laid-back. Some later metal bands even took a cue from the Romantic Era's darker themes. Some lyrics that showcase the darker side of metal include the following from Helter Skelter, which is like a showcase of the Beatles' wilder side. This song is actually considered by some to be one of the first heavy metal songs, as a response to a similar song by the Rolling Stones. The Beatles wanted to prove they could be just as heavy as the Stones, so they added this song to The White Album.

Before the Surrealists were painting their trippy works, Henri Rousseau was busy living his own dream, literally and figuratively. His 1910 masterpiece, The Dream, isn't just some chick checking out the sights in a fantasy world – it's also a reflection of his own personal dreams and aspirations as an artist. For years, Rousseau wanted the art world to give him a shout-out, and he was stuck between a rock and a hard place. On one hand, he wanted to fit in with the cool art kids and follow the latest styles, but on the other hand, he wanted to be true to himself and paint his own way.

To understand The Dream, you gotta know a bit about Rousseau's backstory. He was born on May 21, 1844, in some small town in northwest France. His dad was a hardware dealer who was pretty well-off, but Rousseau didn't get any fancy art training. Instead, he worked for the French government as a toll collector until he was 40. People called him a customs inspector, but that's not exactly what he was. After his first wife and eight little kids died, Rousseau was left with just one kid, Julia, and a whole lot of sadness. Painting was his escape, his way to start fresh. Unlike some other artists of his time, Rousseau wasn't all about painting pretty peasants; he was a folk painter, and his art was all about regular people's hopes and dreams.

It's no wonder Rousseau wanted the art world to like him. I mean, he was basically starting from scratch, and he was doing it at an older age than most artists. Plus, he was competing with some super talented and famous artists. It wasn't until around the same time that Matisse was getting famous that Rousseau started getting recognition for his work. In his book, Modern French Painters, Jan Gordon says that Rousseau and Matisse were like total opposites. Matisse was all about not being boring, while Rousseau just wanted to paint something so normal that people would accept him as a real artist.

A lot of deep thinkers have suggested that ethics and aesthetics are close friends - that truth and beauty are connected in some way. I think there's a reason for this that goes all the way down to the basics. As John Keats says in his poem, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - That's all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Most of what we learn in life comes from school or personal experience, but we tend to appreciate ethics and aesthetics without needing to be taught. Ethics and aesthetics are both about trying to figure out why something is beautiful or moral, as opposed to providing a set of rules for creating good art or good behavior. 

To get to the point, people can never really put their finger on exactly what makes something good or beautiful. Talking about the value of something like the Mona Lisa might involve stuff like background, foreground, or cultural context, but these things don't capture what makes it good art. When people talk about their favorite piece of art, they often say something like "There's just something about it" before getting into the details. I think that both art and morals have this thing that can't be totally explained. As Flannery O'Connor said, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way...you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." No matter how well we describe a work of art, there's always something more to it. I think morality has the same property. As Wittgenstein said, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed / Ethics is transcendental." I think this "something" that's hard to put into words is what makes art and morality so powerful, and it's what connects them.

I believe that morals and art are connected because we experience them at a deep, almost unexplainable level. This connection is even stronger when it comes to literature. As McKean said, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values...Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Germany is a country that's really come together, with its own unique vibe that's all over the place - from the mountains in München to the Baltic Sea in Kiel.  You can feel that culture in Köln, right on the Rhine River, all the way to Dresden on the Elbe. It's no surprise it's got such a cool culture considering it's made up of lots of different tribes and sources. They call it Germania, the land of the Germans, but nobody really knows where the name came from. Some think it's from a tribe called the Tungrians, and they were called Germans before they crossed the Rhine and fought the Gauls (check out Tacitus, 98).

Julius Caesar used the word "Germanus" in his book about the Gallic Wars, which was all about beating up the Gauls and dealing with Germanic tribes that were always crossing the Rhine. He got the word from the Gauls themselves and used it to tell the difference between people he'd already conquered and those he hadn't. He even wrote about how the Germans were always at war with the Gauls in his book. Some people think the name comes from a spear they used in battles called a ger, or maybe from the Old Irish word "garim", which means they were super loud or rowdy. 

In his book, written in 98 AD, Tacitus said that the Germans were basically a pure-blooded people who didn't mix with other cultures. He even wrote about how nobody would just leave Asia or Africa to come to Germany, which was pretty rough and wild. So, the Romans didn't really want to live there, but they did go there to trade and fight sometimes. Germanic tribes started showing up in the first century, and they'd trade goods and skills with the Romans, who mostly just went home after their campaigns.

My eyes were fixed on something in front of me, but my mind was elsewhere, blank and unresponsive.  I went through the motions, staring at this thing, but it was like my brain was in a different room, studying it without really thinking about it.  Thoughts would pop up for a second, and then they'd be gone, like a fleeting thought that never really stuck.  It was like I was just going through the motions, not really thinking for myself, just experiencing whatever I was looking at.

I'd picked up this art book a while back, The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain, after an artist I worked with suggested it.  I'd always wanted to learn how to draw since I was six, and this book was supposed to teach me the basics.  One trick it showed was to draw a square around whatever picture you're looking at, to simplify it and make it easier to understand.  I tried to do that, but at the time, I was so blown away by what I was looking at that I couldn't even think about drawing a frame around it.

I was staring at this bowl of fruit, and all I could do was stand there, frozen in awe.  I thought about all the famous artists who'd done their own weird things with art - Picasso and his blue phase, Monet and his love of greenery, the Renaissance masters and their colorful stuff.  If I wanted to be an artist, then this was my chance to start something new, to make my own art.  I called it Work in Brown.

My hand reached out and picked up my pencil, and for a second, I felt like I was creating something amazing.  But then I had to go use the bathroom, and that's when things started to go wrong.  I tried to, ah, "create" something in the toilet, but it just wouldn't budge.  I was getting a little anxious, and my hand was starting to shake.  I looked at the, um, "art" I was trying to create, and I just couldn't help but frown.  It was a real mess.

I gripped the mop a little tighter, and I thought about how I was going to have to deal with this later.  I was already feeling pretty stressed out, and now I had to add this to the list.  I looked at the, ahem, "masterpiece" in front of me and just shook my head.  It was gonna be a long day...

Teen drivers are a major cause of concern in the US.  Several factors contribute to this problem.  The National Institutes of Health say that one reason is that the teen brain is not ready to handle the risks of driving.  Teens also lack experience, which leads to more fatal accidents, a higher rate of rollover incidents, speeding, and driving off the road.  When teens drive with their friends, the danger increases even more.  A study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center found that the number of traffic accidents goes up as the age of the passenger gets younger.

In an attempt to make driving safer for teens, some states require temporary licenses that limit the number of hours they can drive and don't allow minors as passengers.  However, these licenses are only temporary fixes.  The real issue is that teens are, statistically, not ready to handle the risks and responsibilities of driving.  Marvin Zuckerman, a psychologist, thinks that 18 is still too young for a regular driver's license.  He's done research showing that people under 19-20 often take risks just for the thrill of it.  This makes sense, so it's a good idea to delay driving until the tendency to take risks has decreased.  If we keep giving out driver's licenses to young teens, we'll see more deadly accidents and the death toll will probably get really high.  By 2010, millions of new teen drivers will be on the road.

Making new laws to deal with this issue would be pretty simple.  Schools could still offer driver's education classes to teach future drivers the basics, but no one under 18 could drive.  We could still give out temporary permits before a full license, and require a certain number of driving practice hours.  The number of hours could be the same as most states require now (like 6 hours of driving lessons and 50 hours of practice with an adult in California).  Since this problem affects all states, a national law would be a good way to protect teen drivers across the country.  This idea isn't new, but it could really make a difference.

I spent the day browsing through the early Edison films at the Library of Congress and decided to check out all the trick films from 1895 to 1901. There were fifteen of them, and they're all about using editing tricks to create illusions. I mainly analyzed the poetic aspects of these films and looked at how some of the later ones broke the rules. Back in the day, trick films were pretty set in their ways - they were static, stuck to a frontal proscenium, used long shots, and just one shot per film. It was like a one-trick pony, you know? But around the turn of the century, some films started to get a little wild and crazy and added in some new stuff like multiple shots.

What really stood out to me about these trick films was that they were all shot on interior sets with a proscenium in the background. The camera never moved, no matter what. It was like it was stuck in one place, just like in a play or a magic show. I guess this is where the idea of a static set comes from - it's like a trapped stage. When I watched Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), I noticed that the actors would just move side to side, never walking towards or away from the camera. Even when they left the frame, the camera didn't budge. It was like they were stuck in some kind of weird, two-dimensional world.

These early trick films also stuck to long shots and occasional medium shots. Never any close-ups, just like in a play where the audience sees the whole scene at once. It's like the camera is trying to show you the whole performance at once, like a big ol' play. And the actors never move towards the camera, so you never get any close-ups. It's like they're stuck in some kind of frozen moment in time.

Most of these early trick films are super short, like, under a minute, and they're all about doing one trick and getting out. It's like a magic show, where they just do a few tricks and then it's over. But, when you look closer, you realize that some of these films are actually made up of several short shots joined together to create some crazy illusion. Take The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895) for example - it looks like one shot, but if you really pay attention, you can see where the actual camera cuts happen.

So there's this guy John Taylor from Caroline, and he was super into Republicanism from the get-go. He was a farmer at heart, but even with his farming and his brief stint in politics, he was known for being super outspoken about personal freedom and the government. His love for agriculture basically dictated his views on almost everything, including the government, sovereignty, Constitutionality, and even the judicial system. He was all about preserving and promoting the best of the best when it came to careers, which influenced his arguments on just about everything.

Taylor thought the US had a shot at creating the perfect system because they didn't have any pre-existing traditions to mess things up - it was a blank slate, basically. He was all about natural rights and how they're all connected - if one gets taken away, they all suffer, and the ones that are left are basically worthless. He believed these rights should be off-limits to the government. He thought the so-called "state of nature" was all about people with power and bad intentions getting ahead, but that shouldn't be the case in a civilized society.

To make this ideal society a reality, Taylor believed a government had to be designed with both good and evil in mind. He was pretty rigid in his views on dualistic morality - he thought government is basically just a reflection of human nature. He said that governments have good and bad principles, and good principles are all about protecting private property, improving agriculture, and discouraging capitalism. He thought a government with good principles would be fair no matter who was in charge, but the reality is that governments are usually run by greedy people. He believed self-interest was the driving force behind everything humans do, but it's only bad when it leads to a society that exploits others. A good government is necessary to keep humans' natural badness in check, but it needs to be watched closely to avoid adding any bad principles.

Taylor, like a lot of other super-hardcore Republicans back then, was all about interpreting the Constitution super strictly. He wanted a super limited Federal government that only had the powers explicitly stated in the Constitution. He knew a big Federal government would be expensive and likely to become a dictatorship, but he also thought that just following the literal words of the Constitution without considering the writers' intentions could be super corrupt. And, to him, the Declaration of Independence was basically the US's true charter because it clearly states that we're a bunch of separate states rather than one country.

Looking at Figure 17, it's clear that there was a huge drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. This was pretty discouraging, and it's hard to say exactly why it happened. One thing that might have contributed to it is that winter set in at our New England campus, which probably led to fewer people biking or walking to school. It's also possible that the end of the fall semester and the holiday season just got in the way – everyone was too busy finishing schoolwork and grades to bother filling out the log. Plus, the month-long break at the end of the semester probably meant a lot of people didn't need to come to campus at all. When classes resumed in January, we saw another low number of submissions, but that still doesn't explain the dip in February. It could be that people just got bored with the project after the initial excitement wore off. To counteract this, we tried something called the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which actually worked and boosted log submissions for that month. We figured out that one of our biggest challenges was getting people to stay engaged despite the natural decrease in interest, and also dealing with the holiday and semester breaks that are just part of higher education. 

Another problem we faced was that a lot of people really love driving their cars, and that's just a big part of our culture. So we had to come up with incentives to get people to try alternative modes of transportation. We gave out some pretty cool prizes, like gift cards to restaurants, coffee shops, and stores. It would have been interesting to see if bigger prizes, like a new bike or a hybrid car, would have made a difference – but unfortunately, we didn't get to try that out. We kept the same type of prizes throughout the project, but if we had announced some bigger prizes in December or January, it might have kept people engaged instead of losing interest. I mean, who wouldn't want to win a bike or a car?

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is pretty cool because it's like a security that copies an index, a commodity, or a bunch of assets, just like an index fund, but it's way more flexible and trades like a stock on the exchange.  It gives you the benefits of an index fund, like diversification, and the perks of owning a single stock, like being able to sell short, buy on margin, and even purchase just one share at a time.  These benefits are super attractive, but the fees for ETFs are way lower than the average mutual fund.  However, there are some downsides, like you have to pay a commission on any trade involving ETFs, just like with a stock order.  Another awesome thing about ETFs is that there's a huge variety of funds available.  But, it's always smart to be a savvy financial investor and check if the benefits you're told about, like diversification, are actually real, and how real they are.  For now, we're going to check out the ETF IHF and compare it to its top 10 holdings to see if owning a single ETF is just as good as owning a bunch of individual stocks.  

To make things less overwhelming, we're only going to look at the top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of the ETF's total assets.  The top 10 holdings are listed below, along with their percentage of the total assets.

By looking at how well these 10 stocks represent the ETF as a whole, we can use the current percentage of assets to calculate their contributions to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio was made up entirely of these 10 stocks, in the same proportions as the ETF has them.  The calculations for Beta and Return are included in the chart below.

From the chart, it's pretty clear that a portfolio made up of just the top 10 holdings would return 6.11% more than the ETF, a 16% increase in returns.  It's also pretty evident that the Beta of the top 10 holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF as a whole.  So far, it seems like a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could give you a higher return with a lower Beta.  But, there's a chance that the means of these two portfolios might not be all that different statistically.

To figure out if these portfolios are statistically different, we calculated the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and compared it to the standard deviation of the ETF IHF.

Dream-Land is often considered one of Edgar Allan Poe's improved poems. In this poem, Poe uses the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott thinks is linked back to the writings of Virgil. However, it's also possible that Poe got it from a more recent source - he was a big fan of German authors. 

This connection is pretty significant because it shows Poe's familiarity with Goethe's work. Karl J. Arndt noticed in his book that Poe's poem Politian is similar to Goethe's Mignon, which led him to believe that Poe might have been inspired by Goethe. 

The Oxford Companion to English Literature says that Goethe was famous for writing the poetic drama Faust, which came out in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year he died. There's a short poem called "The King of Thulé" hidden inside the second part of Faust. It's about a king who loses his wife and starts drinking heavily, then decides to die after remembering his dead queen. He throws away his goblet and walks to a cliff, where he dies. The King of Thulé and the character in Dream-Land have some pretty strong similarities, maybe even a dark opposite of Poe's own struggles with loss and drinking. 

Faust was also turned into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, just a year before Poe used the term Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum". Poe mentions Thule twice in his collected works - once in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and twice in "Dream-Land" to bookend the poem. "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land", the speaker describes Thule as a dark, lonely place with dead friends and a world without color. This sounds a lot like the King of Thulé in Goethe's poem, who's just lost his wife and is feeling pretty down. It's like the speaker in "Dream-Land" stepped right into Goethe's poem. 

Goethe was a pretty big deal in the literary world, and Poe would have likely known about him, even if it was just through his respect for Tennyson. Poe said something about how he admired Tennyson, and he would have been exposed to Goethe's work through all the reproductions that were going on after the original publication.

In California, if a customer slipped and fell on an applesauce spill in a grocery store and got hurt, can they get punitive damages if the store manager knew about the spill but didn't clean it up for half an hour because he was too busy eating dinner? A judge's probably not gonna dismiss the customer's claim for punitive damages right away. To win their case, the customer needs to show that the manager acted with a super bad and on purpose disregard for how his actions would affect people, and that his actions were really, really bad. The customer can argue that the manager should've known how bad it would be not to clean up the spill because lots of other people had slipped and gotten hurt in the store before, and he still did nothing. The customer's argument that the manager's actions were super bad isn't super strong, but it's still kind of reasonable. This is because the store had six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009 and the manager didn't do anything to make the store safer.

On October 13th at 5:00 pm, an employee of D&D Markets told the manager, Paul Martin, that there was a big applesauce spill in one of the aisles. Martin was like, "I'm on dinner break, I don't have time for customer complaints." Fifteen minutes later, another employee told Martin about the spill again, and he said the same thing. At 5:30 pm, the customer, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill and hurt her back really badly. Before Palmer got hurt, there were already five other slip-and-fall incidents reported at D&D's in 2009. Palmer is suing D&D for both regular damages and punitive damages, and we're figuring out whether to ask the judge to throw out the part of the claim about the punitive damages.

In California, people can get punitive damages if someone broke a law that wasn't related to a contract and acted with a really bad attitude, like being super mean or deceitful. The law says "malice" means either doing something on purpose to hurt someone, or doing something really, really bad with a total disregard for other people's rights or safety. Courts have said that it's like when someone knows that their actions are going to hurt people, but they do it anyway because they don't care. That's basically what the teacher in the Taylor case said in 1979.

It's crazy to think it's been almost four years since I took that course on Islam at CBC.  We had this huge debate in class about whether or not Islam is a hostile religion.  I still think that question is super relevant today, especially considering how media's view on Islam has changed since 9/11.  It's wild to think that back in 2001, we wouldn't have even considered a presidential candidate with a Muslim background like Barack Obama.  

The Prophet's biography really got me thinking.  I learned in class that Muhammad was supposed to be some kind of conqueror who forced people to convert to Islam, but the biography paints a whole different picture.  It's like, Muhammad comes across as this humble guy who's been misunderstood and even humbled himself to others.  People started to see the 'truth' in his teachings and came to him on their own.  That's pretty different from what I thought I knew about him.

What's also tripping me out is how similar the ministries of Jesus and Muhammad's 'miracles' are.  Like, there's this one story where Muhammad takes some mutton and milk and it's enough for 40 people.  I think the writers wanted to make Muhammad seem like this humble prophet who didn't need to prove anything, just lived in truth and did miracles.  That's kinda problematic because it downplays Jesus' life and personhood.  It's like they're stealing from Jesus and trying to pass it off as Muhammad's story.

There are a lot of stories in the biography that are presented as 'proof' of people converting to Islam on their own, but they're all from third-party sources.  I mean, it's like the author's trying to say 'Hey, I heard from so-and-so who heard from so-and-so,' and it just doesn't feel real.  It makes me skeptical.

What really gets me is that they're trying to make Muhammad out to be this godly, humble, and wise guy.  But history doesn't back that up, and I wonder if Muslims today even know the real story behind Muhammad's rise to power.

Looking back, it seems that the teachings and ideas that Jesus lived by got lost in the shuffle when Christianity started evolving after his death.  If we look at Christian history in general, it's clear that it's strayed further and further away from its roots.  It's like the whole world is moving forward with a growing awareness and a trend towards progress, but the traditional folks are still stuck in their ways and resistant to new ideas.  They might not be influential enough to make a huge impact, though.  I think down the line, people will start to become more aware of their Christian history and wonder what the original plans were.  They'll start to figure out which parts of the religion were added over time and what the actual message of Jesus was.  It might take a while - decades or even centuries - but eventually, things will swing back around.  A big shift will happen in Christian history, and we'll move back to the way things were when Jesus first started spreading the word.  Instead of all these added layers of doctrine, we'll strip them away, one by one, until we're back to the basics of what Jesus taught us about God.  When this movement picks up speed in the US and Europe, it'll be like a big wave that sweeps through and changes things.  People will start to worship like we did back in Jesus' day, following what he said and believed.  The church as an institution will stay strong, but it'll lead people back to the basics, not the complicated ideas that have been added over time.  You'll see a big change from all the differences within Christianity to tons of similarities and a more uniform way of thinking.  It's not the first time this has happened, either - think about how the Roman Empire used to persecute Christians, but then they became the Christian empire, or how the US used to have African-American leaders at the bottom of society, but now they're leading the way.  A similar thing is going to happen in Christianity, where people will go back to the source and make things simpler and more unified.  To make all this happen, we need to start seeing Jesus' words as metaphors, not as literal statements.  So, let's go back to the beginning - what was Christianity like back in the day?  If we go way back, we find that it all started with Judaism, which was the core of the Christian faith.  By the time the Romans took over Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., Jewish people already believed in one God, had a revealed religion, and followed the Hebrew scriptures.  But they weren't all on the same page - there were Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a bunch of regular folks, all with different ideas.

I think that The Jungle really shows how humans on the inside are pretty selfish and only think about themselves. They just try to make their lives better and don't really care about anyone else. This is super clear in the book when you look at the big factory owners and managers. All they care about is making their companies huge and rich and they don't even think about the people or the planet getting hurt because of it. Upton Sinclair writes some pretty sick stuff, like, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world". He's basically painting a picture of how messed up the pollution is and how the owners don't even care about the animals or people getting hurt. They're all about making a buck, and don't care if it hurts the environment or the people working for them. Sinclair says it pretty bluntly, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar". The owners and managers are all about making money, and they'll do whatever it takes to get it. They make people work crazy hours and then just get rid of them when they're not making enough money. Back then, there weren't really any laws to protect workers, so the owners could do whatever they wanted. The people working in the factories and living in Packingtown were basically treated like slaves. There were no organizations helping them or giving them information, and the unions were actually just making money off the poor workers. The workers were basically trapped in this system and were described as slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Sometimes authors really know how to get you to feel a certain way about important stuff. They have a bunch of tricks up their sleeve to do this, and some of them work way better than others. In his book The Great Gatsby, F. Scott Fitzgerald is like a master of these tricks. One of the things he does is pair up words that don't usually go together to make you think about a subject in a certain way. Another thing he does is take a symbol and give it meaning, then use it again to make you feel something specific. Fitzgerald used this last trick with lots of colors, including gold, green, but also white/gray and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, he builds up meaning for white/gray and red/pink, then uses that meaning to make you feel a certain way about something important.

Fitzgerald makes white/gray into a symbol of something pretty specific: uniformity. White is like, higher class and nicer, while gray is more old and faded. He sets up this meaning at the very beginning of the book by using these colors all the time. Like, Daisy and Jordan are always wearing white, and not just them - everyone's always wearing white: Nick wears white flannels to Gatsby's party, Tom wears a white shirt when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is super pale and white. Actually, the only time people aren't wearing white is when Nick's describing Gatsby's party: the halls are all gaudy and bright. Fitzgerald keeps using these colors to describe regular, boring stuff too: as Nick goes to work, he goes down the white canyons of lower New York, the names of people at Gatsby's parties are just gray names on Nick's schedule, Catherine's apartment is just one part of a long row of white apartment buildings, and so on. He even describes plain people or places as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy had a white girlhood together, there are gray cars and gray land in the valley of ashes, the little Italian kid in the train is gray, and the dog-seller is a gray old man.

After Fitzgerald builds up enough meaning with white/gray, he uses them to make you feel like some subjects are unimportant or uniform. This starts with Daisy. After a while without using these colors much, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as wearing white in a little white roadster, and you start to see her as just a uniform thing, something Gatsby wants but isn't really a person. He uses this technique with Daisy a bunch of times to make you feel like she's just a uniform addition, like when there's a gray haze around her fur collar, or when she's wearing a white dress before Tom and Gatsby's big encounter.

San Diego County is super good at growing food, thanks to its awesome weather and lots of sunshine. They grow all sorts of cool stuff like tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, and even tree fruits like peaches and lemons. Berries and honey are also super popular, and people love getting peppers. There's a huge demand for organic food in the area, and lots of local groups have super long waiting lists for their community-supported agriculture programs. People in San Diego also love buying organic eggs and milk. Many organic farms in the area even let you tour their operations and explore the land for hiking, birdwatching, and other fun stuff. This kind of setup is perfect for farmers who want to get government help while keeping the land healthy and making money through tours and other programs.

The benefits of organic farming are pretty sweet, but it's not all sunshine and rainbows. For one, it takes a lot more work and management to get rid of pests and weeds without using chemicals, and you might lose more crops than with regular farming methods. Small organic farms also can't compete with big operations when it comes to efficiency. To make things better for wildlife, you've got to do things like plant cover crops, help animals move around the land, get rid of invasive species, and make sure the plants have the right conditions to thrive. That's a lot more work and costs more money, so farmers might need some help or expertise to make it all work.

I picked a specific piece of land near the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California, as my example. It's 160 acres of beautiful chaparral, grassland, and oak woodland, right next to the Cleveland National Forest. This area is part of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion, which is covered in the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan looks at over a hundred different plants and animals, some of which are super endangered, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the mountain yellow-legged frog. Others are in trouble and might be listed as endangered soon, like the burrowing owl.

This land has been home to Native Americans for who-knows-how-long and was later settled by cattle ranchers and people who sold wood in the 1800s. It was part of an original homestead patent, so it was probably used for grazing and wood production for a long time. I picked a real piece of property from a website and looked into government programs to see what a small farmer might do to make organic farming work and keep the land safe for wildlife. I used a local organic farm in the same area as my example.

Culture is a key factor in any negotiation, but it's often more about what it's not than what it actually is. It's not one-size-fits-all; instead, it's a complex and multifaceted thing that can change from situation to situation. You can't make blanket statements like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" because they're just too broad and oversimplify things. What's more helpful is understanding how a culture affects the negotiation at hand and how its attitudes might impact the talks. When you deal with a foreign culture, you're bound to compare it to your own, and that's when the real learning happens.

To get a handle on a different culture, you might need to study its history or learn about its prejudices. The goal is to accept it for what it is, not to judge or try to change it, especially when you're in a weaker bargaining position. If you're negotiating on foreign soil, showing respect for local traditions and customs can be a game-changer. It can help you get past any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

But culture isn't just about national or international differences; it's also present within companies, too. Corporate culture can vary wildly depending on the company, from super-serious work hours to a more relaxed schedule. You can see evidence of it in things like dress codes, communication styles, and who gets hired. Take American companies, for example - they're all different, even within the same country. And it's not just about big differences between companies; even within the same company, there can be regional and urban/suburban differences. So, it's not always easy to tell what's going on beneath the surface.

When it comes to values, that's where things get really important. They're what give a culture its underlying reasons for being. If saving face or community harmony is a big deal in a culture, you can bet that a negotiator won't go out of their way to shame their company or boss in public. And if a culture values getting a hard bargain, they won't be in a rush to settle just to get a deal done. Knowing these things can help you prepare for a negotiation, but it's also a good idea to get to know your opponent on a personal level to really make the negotiation work.

"The fool has said, 'There is no God.' This quote from Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible is also the starting point for St. Anselm's argument on God's existence and is found in the beginning of his reasoning. It's interesting to note that Thomas Aquinas seems to hold a similar view as well. Since we're about to discuss both of their arguments, which are basically about the same thing, we'll assume they're both right about the existence of God - the God of the Bible. If we consider a different version of God, it would be hard to compare their arguments because they're more or less just trying to prove the existence of the one in the Bible. I think what I'm getting at is that while both of them make some solid points, neither one really does a complete job of proving God's existence.

Let's take a look at St. Anselm's argument first. Anselm basically says that to find out about God, you can look inside yourself. He says that because we already know God exists in our minds, it's impossible to imagine a world without him. When you break it down, he's saying that you don't need any outside evidence to prove God's existence - it's all about what you already know inside your head. This idea is often called faith, which means accepting something without all the facts. It's a pretty different approach from what St. Thomas Aquinas is saying.

St. Thomas thinks that you can use logic and evidence to prove God's existence without relying on faith. This would be super helpful for spreading Christianity because it would make it easier to convince new people to join without them having to believe something without proof. He's got five different logical arguments to back this up: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. What he's basically saying is that you can use logic to figure out that God exists, even if you can't see him. For example, imagine if someone told you that you're missing a puzzle piece, and you put all the others together - you can still figure out what the missing piece looks like without actually seeing it.

It's a pretty weird feeling thinking that around 2,500 years ago or so, a prince would grow up to become the Buddha. I guess this guy would ditch the whole royalty thing and find enlightenment, which, in turn, led to the creation of Buddhism. The most traditional branch of Buddhism is called Theravada Buddhism. I'm pretty sure it's changed a lot since the Buddha's time, though. You can see the difference in a place like Sri Lanka, where they have this wacky water-cutting ceremony. Everyone, monks and regular people alike, participate in it, and it's got some meaning, even though the Buddha never talked about it. These differences are all over the place, from the silly traditions to the deeper stuff that makes up the core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community has had to modify its main ideas over time, both on its own and due to external influences. Sometimes these changes come from people who don't believe in Buddhism, but other times they come from within the community itself.

You might hear some new terms in this discussion, so let's define them. An internal force refers to something that comes from within the Buddhist community, while an external force is something from outside. A hostile force is anything that harms the Buddhist community, while a benign force doesn't try to hurt or help, even if it ends up doing one or the other by accident. These terms will pop up a lot in what I'm about to say.

First off, let's talk about the basics of Theravada Buddhism – the core stuff that makes it tick. Buddhists put their trust in three key things: the Buddha, the Dhamma (which is essentially all the Buddhist texts), and the Sangha (the community). The Dhamma is made up of three main parts – the Tripitaka – which includes the Sutta Pitaka (all the Suttas), the Vinaya Pitaka (the rules of conduct), and the Abhidhamma Pitaka (the metaphysical stuff). The metaphysical stuff covers ideas like there's no permanent soul, life is full of suffering, and nothing lasts forever. If you can wrap your head around these concepts, you can break free from this cycle of death and rebirth. Along with that, you'll also kick the habit of desiring stuff, hating things, and being delusional. The Vinaya Pitaka lays out the rules for life, with five precepts for regular people (don't kill, don't lie, don't steal, don't be all weird about sex, and don't get drunk) and a bunch more rules for monks. The most important idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths: first, life is suffering; second, attachments cause suffering; and third, suffering can be overcome.

The US and Mexico have a pretty wild history that dates back to 1836 and lasted 57 years, from then to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p.145).  The craziest part of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the US took down Mexico and got its hands on Texas and the American Southwest.  There were other smaller skirmishes between the two nations, but the fighting finally died down just before the First World War.  It all started because Americans and Mexicans had major disagreements about stuff like religion, culture, and stuff they thought was important, and they also had huge differences over what they wanted to gain. (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31).  

This rivalry thing isn't unique to the US and Mexico, by the way.  Lots of countries that share borders have clashes of interests that lead to them becoming rivals.  The US and Mexico aren't that different from other countries like this.  David M. Pletcher (1977) said that "Only in Mexico and Cuba can you find long-lasting American diplomatic problems" (p. 41).  Both of these countries are right next to the US and have been at odds with it, while other Latin American countries get along pretty well with the US.  

Religious differences caused a huge rift between the US and Mexico, and this is something that's happened to a lot of other countries too.  Sally Frahm (2001) said that "if Americans were opposed to fascism and communism in the 20th century, in the 18th and 19th they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p.86).  It's kinda like how the Cold War was a mix of ideological struggles and competing interests, but in this case, it was more about the US and Mexico having different ideas about what was important.  This distrust started because the US and Mexico inherited it from their former colonial rulers - the English and Spanish.  This made it tough for the two countries to have a good relationship.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) counted 17 disputes between the US and Mexico during the 57-year rivalry period.  Most of these disputes were about border stuff, like bandits and outlaws crossing the border and causing trouble.  It wasn't until both countries started using military force to control their borders that things started to calm down (Schmitt 1974, p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) said the rivalry started to fade away as "Mexico became dependent on the US in a big way" (p. 109) and eventually ended when American ambitions changed from trying to take over land to trying to influence Mexico's economy (p.110) in the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I hit rock bottom after a mysterious illness left me disabled and unable to work. At the time, I was a nurse with a dream of becoming a scientist or journalist, but life had other plans. People kept telling me, "You'll always find a job; people will always get sick," so I chose nursing as a secure career choice. Little did I know that my security would soon be turned upside down.

Fast forward to my life at 46: I'm single, broke, and living on disability checks. I've lost count of the days when I thought I had nothing left to call my own. Every day is a struggle to survive, and my self-esteem takes a hit. But one thing I know for sure is that I couldn't have made it this far without my family and a few true friends. When disaster strikes, you realize how fragile you are, and how much you need the help of others.

My point is that life is full of emergencies – big and small. No matter how prepared you are, some things are just too big to handle on your own. So, let's stop relying solely on the government to save us and start building a safety net of our own. Instead of bailing out to build our own fallout shelters, let's learn to trust each other and ask for help when we need it.

The Conservatives talk about rugged individualism, but it was actually community and compassion that kept our ancestors going in tough times. The pioneers who trekked across the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it by going it alone – they relied on each other for support.

So, be prepared, but don't forget the importance of community. I've got my disaster kit, first aid supplies, and a stash of canned goods, but I also try to know my neighbors and look out for them. It's time for us to stop relying solely on ourselves and start building a network of people who will help each other out when things get tough.

It's still a mystery why organisms evolve the way they do. There are probably some rules or boundaries that determine which way they change over time. Even back in 1917, D'Arcy Thompson pointed out that biologists are still pretty clueless about describing the simplest living things in math terms. But more recently, math has been used to figure out how certain types of animals build their shells over time, like the way they grow and develop (Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study is working on using math to understand how animals like the ones in the Prunum family grow their shells and change over time. We're combining math with experiments to see what makes some of these animals change in certain ways. We looked at X-ray pictures of different Prunum species and used the information to create math models of their shells. These models helped us see what their shells could look like if they changed in different ways. Now we're combining these models with our experiments to learn more about how these animals evolved over time.

Think of a shell like a tube that moves through space over time. It's like a big spiral that goes around in a circle, and each part of the spiral is called a whorl. The middle of the shell is like an imaginary stick that runs through the middle of the spiral. This stick is called the columella. The speed at which the spiral grows can change, and the lines that separate each whorl are called sutures. Most shells have a big spiral at the end, which is called the body whorl. The rest of the spiral is called the spire. The tip of the spire is the apex, and the other end is the base. The animal sticks out of its shell through a hole called the aperture.

You can look at a shell from different angles, like looking at the top, bottom, front, or back. Most people look at shells with the front side facing them and the top pointing up. 

There's a way to count the whorls on a shell. First, look at the shell from the top and find the first line where the whorls start to separate. Then draw a line to divide the shell in two. Count the whorls from this line, and you can even estimate a quarter of a whorl if you need to.

A shell is like a series of holes that move through time and space as the animal grows its shell. You can follow the path of the holes by looking at the center of each whorl and the size of the hole. This path can be drawn and mathematically explained. Once you have the math formula, you can change the rules and see how the animal's shell changes.

It's been a decade since Indonesia's neonatal and infant mortality rates have changed much.  Even though the country is doing pretty well in achieving some of the Millennium Development Goals, like getting clean water and sanitation, the progress in child and maternal health is nowhere near what it needs to be to reach its targets by 2015.  In the next few sections, I'll be talking about the reasons behind this lack of improvement, and you'll see why Indonesia needs to focus on strengthening its healthcare system rather than just working on individual programs.

Indonesia has made some progress in getting skilled workers at births, with 72% of births now getting this kind of care.  But this number is a bit misleading since it includes traditional workers like midwives who can't provide medical help if a pregnancy gets complicated - which is why a lot of maternal deaths are due to hemorrhage.  Additionally, there's been a drop in the percentage of kids under five who get treated by a health professional for diarrhea, and the data on post-natal care is pretty incomplete, but it's clear that it's a big problem all over the country.

C-section rates are still pretty low at 4%, and that's got some major implications.  The rate is 7% in cities, but only 2% in rural areas, which shows that healthcare services are mostly focused on city areas.  There's also a huge gap in access to healthcare between the richest and poorest families - 27% to be exact.  This means the poor are having a hard time getting the care they need, probably because they can't afford it.

So, the big question is how to make things better, starting with getting more healthcare services available.  Should Indonesia focus on developing special programs or just making the overall healthcare system stronger?  It's clear that special programs can get fast results, but they also have some big drawbacks.  One problem is that when you invest a lot in one area, other areas might get left behind.  Another issue is that all these separate programs can get really confusing and make a lot of extra paperwork.

Victorian novels are known for their intricate details and their focus on the aristocracy of the time period.  Two novels that deviate from this norm are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights.  Instead of following the typical Victorian style, these novels incorporate a sense of mystery and a touch of the bizarre, which helps to deepen our understanding of the characters' motivations and emotions. These atypical elements give us insight into their inner workings, making them feel more real and relatable.

As Fagin's character in Oliver Twist was walking between Sikes and Crackit, arguing, he couldn't shake off the feeling that he was still there; the words they were saying echoed in his mind, and when he snapped out of it, he found himself talking to them.  Suddenly, he jumped back at the sound of gunfire and was whisked away by an unseen force.  Through this disorienting experience, a nagging sense of pain lingered, wearing him down and tormenting him.

In both novels, this sense of mystery often manifests itself through dream sequences or dreamlike states.  In Oliver Twist, these bizarre events give us a glimpse into Oliver's inner world, revealing what hurts him and how he perceives the events unfolding around him.  When Oliver is shot in chapter 28, he relives the experience vividly, as if it's a dream, while struggling to find help.  The passage emphasizes Oliver's lack of control over his situation, as well as his dire circumstances, which is evident in his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit.  The shooting overwhelms him, numbing all his senses, and he feels his despair wash over him again, this time laced with fear rather than surprise.
